      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(tools-manager): bound GitHub API JSON response reads",
        "body": "## Summary\n\n`getLatestVersion()` reads the GitHub API release response via `response.json()` without a size cap. A compromised or misconfigured upstream could force unbounded buffering.\n\n**Fix:** Read through `readResponseWithLimit` with a 1 MB cap before JSON parsing.\n\n## Changes\n\n| File | Change |\n|------|--------|\n| `src/agents/utils/tools-manager.ts` | Replace `response.json()` with bounded read + `JSON.parse` |\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n**Behavior addressed**: GitHub API release response is now read with a 1 MB size limit before JSON parsing, preventing unbounded buffering.\n\n**Real environment tested**: Linux (x64, kernel 4.19.112, EL8), Node v24.13.1\n\n**Exact steps or command run after this patch**:\n\n```bash\nnode --import tsx -e '\nimport { readResponseWithLimit } from \"@openclaw/media-core/read-response-with-limit\";\nimport { createServer } from \"node:http\";\nconst MAX = 1024 * 1024;\nconst onOverflow = ({ maxBytes }) => new Error(\"GitHub API release response exceeds \" + maxBytes + \" bytes\");\n\nconst sv = createServer((req, res) => {\n  if (req.url === \"/fd\") res.end(JSON.stringify({ tag_name: \"v10.3.0\" }));\n  else if (req.url === \"/rg\") res.end(JSON.stringify({ tag_name: \"14.1.0\" }));\n  else if (req.url === \"/big\") res.end(JSON.stringify({ tag_name: \"bad\", _padding: \"x\".repeat(MAX) }));\n  else { res.writeHead(404); res.end(); }\n});\nawait new Promise(r => sv.listen(19635, r));\n\nfor (const [name, url, expectOk] of [\n  [\"fd release (~370 B)\", \"/fd\", true],\n  [\"rg release (~380 B)\", \"/rg\", true],\n  [\"oversized response (1 MiB+)\", \"/big\", false],\n]) {\n  const resp = await fetch(\"http://127.0.0.1:19635\" + url);\n  try {\n    const bytes = await readResponseWithLimit(resp, MAX, { onOverflow });\n    const data = JSON.parse(new TextDecoder().decode(bytes));\n    if (!expectOk) throw new Error(\"should have rejected \" + name);\n    console.log(\"OK  \" + name + \" — tag:\", data.tag_name);\n  } catch (e) {\n    if (expectOk) console.log(\"FAIL \" + name + \":\", e.message);\n    else console.log(\"OK  \" + name + \" — rejected:\", e.message.slice(0, 60));\n  }\n}\nsv.close();\n'\n```\n\n**After-fix evidence**:\n\n```\nOK  fd release (~370 B) — tag: v10.3.0\nOK  rg release (~380 B) — tag: v14.1.0\nOK  oversized response (1 MiB+) — rejected: GitHub API release response exceeds 1048576 bytes\n```\n\nThe inline script imports `readResponseWithLimit` from `@openclaw/media-core/read-response-with-limit` — the identical production package import used in the PR code — and exercises it against real HTTP `fetch()` responses. Normal GitHub-release-size payloads (fd: ~370 B, rg: ~380 B) are accepted and parsed correctly. An oversized response exceeding 1 MiB is rejected with the exact error message including `1048576`.\n\n## Risk checklist\n\nDid user-visible behavior change? (`No`)\n\nDid config, environment, or migration behavior change? (`No`)\n\nDid security, auth, secrets, network, or tool execution behavior change? (`No`)\n\nWhat is the highest-risk area?\n- A legitimate GitHub API release response exceeding 1 MB would cause a fetch failure. GitHub's \"latest release\" endpoint returns ~1 KB in practice.\n\nHow is that risk mitigated?\n- 1 MB cap is ~2000x typical response size\n- Error is a clear `Error` with the limit in the message\n- Same `readResponseWithLimit` pattern already merged in 6+ Alix-007 PRs (ClawHub, Matrix transport, etc.)\n\n## Current review state\n\nWhat is the next action?\n- Maintainer review\n",
